text: Synthesis of enantiomerically pure juglomycin C and NHAB Shogo Kamo, Sayako Maruo, Kouji Kuramochi *, Kazunori Tsubaki Graduate School for Life and Environmental Sciences, Kyoto Prefectural University, 1-5 Shimogamo Hangi-cho, Sakyo-ku, Kyoto 606-8522, Japan Article history: Received 2 March 2015 Received in revised form 18 March 2015 Accepted 19 March 2015 Available online xxx Keywords: Juglomycin C (S)-NHAB Naphthoquinone Stereoselective aldol reaction Chiral sulfoxide Juglomycin C (1) was isolated from Streptomyces sp. 815 and 3094 and showed moderate antibacterial activity against Bacillus subtilis and Escherichia coli (Fig. 1).1 Juglomycins A (2) and B (3) were isolated from the same strain1 and Streptomyces sp. 190e2,2 respectively. The absolute conﬁguration of 2 was determined to be 3R,4R with X-ray crystallography, and compounds 1 and 3 were subsequently determined to be 3S and 3R,4S, respectively.3 1,4- Naphthoquinone-8-hydroxy-3-[(3S)-acetoxybutyric ((S)- NHAB, 4) was isolated from a disruptant of the actVI-ORFA gene for biosynthesis of actinorhodin in Streptomyces coelicolor A3(2).4 Compounds 1 and 4 are potential intermediates in the bio- juglomycins A and B.5 The syntheses of naph- synthesis of thoquinone derivatives structurally related to juglomycin C (1) and NHAB (4) have been reported;6 however, there have been no re- ports of the synthesis of 1 and 4.

Several pyranonaphthoquinones such as frenolicin B (5),7 deoxyfrenolicin (6),7,8 kalafungin (7),9 nanaomycin A (8)10 have been isolated (Fig. 2).11 Interestingly, nanaomycin D (9)12 and YS- 02931Kb (dihydrokalafungin; 10),13 which are enantiomers of kalafungin (7) and nanaomycin A (8), respectively, were isolated. Thus, it is important to prepare both enantiomers of natural naphthoquinones in enantiomerically pure form for biological studies such as investigations of their structure-activity relation- ships and biosynthetic pathways. kpu.ac.jp (K. The synthesis of both enantiomers of juglomycin C and NHAB in enantiomerically pure form is reported. The stereoselective aldol reaction of both enantiomers of a chiral sulfoxide with an aldehyde was used for construction of the stereogenic center. This derivative could be synthesized using the stereoselective aldol reaction of (S)- tert-butyl (p-tolylsulﬁnyl)acetate (14) with aldehyde 13, followed by removal of the chiral auxiliary.6f The chiral center at C-3 in (2S,3S)-12 would be introduced with formation of the complex between the magnesium enolate derived from (S)-14 and aldehyde 13.14 Aldehyde 13 can be prepared from juglone according to the method developed by Masquelin et al.6e Chiral sulfoxide (S)-14 originates from (þ)-menthol.14a Unnatural (R)-juglomycin C and (R)-NHAB would be prepared using the aldol reaction between 13 and (R)-14. 2.2. Synthesis of aldehyde 13

Aldehyde 13 was synthesized from methoxymethyl (MOM)- protected juglone 1515 (Scheme 2). Reduction of 15 with sodium dithionite, and treatment of the resultant hydroquinone with allyl bromide in the presence of potassium carbonate gave 16. After the hydroxy group in 16 was protected as its methyl ether, the thermal Claisen rearrangement of the methyl ether in degassed N,N-dieth- ylaniline gave 17 in 77% over two steps. When dimethylformamide (DMF), o-dichlorobenzene or decaline was used as the solvent, deprotection of the MOM group in the methyl ether of 16 and 17 was also observed. The hydroxyl group in 17 was protected as tert- butyldimethylsilyl (TBS) ether 18. Dihydroxylation of 18 with a catalytic amount of osmium tetraoxide and N-methylmorpholine N-oxide (NMO), followed by cleavage of the resultant 1,2-diol with sodium periodate gave 13. 2.3. Synthesis of juglomycin C and (S)-NHAB The ﬁnal steps in the synthesis of juglomycin C and (S)-NHAB are depicted in Scheme 3. An aldol reaction between 13 and (S)-14 using tert-butylmagnesium chloride gave a mixture of (2S,3S)-12 and a minor diastereomer in overall 72% yield.16 Removal of the chiral sulfoxide auxiliary with samarium iodide gave (S)-11 in a quantitative yield. The enantiomeric excess was determined with Scheme 2. Synthesis of aldehyde 13.

chiral HPLC (CHIRALPAK IC column) to be 74%. Oxidation of (S)-11 with cerium ammonium nitrate followed by re- crystallization of the resulting naphthoquinone gave (S)-19 in 69% yield. Because both enantiomers of 19 were difﬁcult to separate by chiral HPLC, the enantiomeric excess of (S)-19 was determined after acetylation. Acetylation of (S)-19 gave (S)-20. The enantiomeric excess of (S)-20 was determined to be >99%. Thus, the enantio- meric excess of (S)-19 was enhanced from 74% to >99% by re- crystallization. Deprotection of the MOM and tert-butyl groups in (S)-19 with triﬂuoroacetic acid (TFA) gave juglomycin C (1) in 81% yield. The 1H and 13C NMR spectra of synthetic 1 were identical to those reported for natural 1.1 The speciﬁc rotation values for syn- thetic 1 and natural 1 were [a]D 24 (cid:2)49.6 (c 0.74, MeOH) and [a]D 25 (cid:2)51.2 (c 0.5, MeOH),1 respectively. Deprotection of the MOM and tert-butyl groups in (S)-20 with TFA afforded (S)-NHAB (4). The 1H and 13C NMR spectra of synthetic (S)-4 matched those reported for (S)-NHAB.4 The speciﬁc rotation of (S)-4 ([a]D 24 (cid:2)80.3 (c 0.30, CHCl3)) was identical to that of (S)-NHAB ([a]D (cid:2)82.4 (c 0.05, CHCl3)). The S conﬁguration at C-3 in the major product obtained by the aldol reaction between 13 and (S)-14 was reconﬁrmed through the synthesis of naturally occurring juglomycin C and (S)-NHAB.

Synthesis of ent-juglomycin C and (R)-NHAB ent-Juglomycin C and (R)-NHAB were prepared using chiral sulfoxide (R)-14, which originated from ((cid:2))-menthol (Scheme 4). An aldol reaction between 13 and (R)-14 afforded (2R,3R)-12, to- gether with a minor diastereomer in 79% yield over two steps. Removal of the chiral sulfoxide gave (R)-11. The enantiomeric ex- cess of (R)-11 was 82%. Oxidation of (R)-11 and recrystallization of the product yielded (R)-19 in 70% yield. The enantiomeric excess of (R)-19 was determined to be >99% by chiral HPLC analysis of its acetylated product (R)-20. Deprotection of (R)-19 and (R)-20 gave ent-juglomycin C and (R)-NHAB, respectively. The speciﬁc rotation of ent-juglomycin C and (R)-NHAB are [a]D 22 þ59.5 (c 0.42, MeOH) and [a]D 23 þ87.8 (c 0.50, CHCl3), respectively.

In conclusion, both enantiomers of juglomycin C and NHAB were prepared in enantiomerically pure form. The stereoselective aldol reaction of both enantiomers of the chiral sulfoxide with the appropriate aldehyde was used for construction of the stereogenic center.6f,14b,14c The enantiomeric purity of the precursors was con- ﬁrmed by chiral HPLC analysis. Juglomycin C and ent-juglomycin C were prepared in 18.0% and 14.8% yields, respectively, and in 11 steps from known MOM-protected juglone. (S)- and (R)-NHAB were prepared in 17.1% and 18.7% yield, respectively, and in 12 steps from MOM-protected juglone. Biological studies on the synthetic compounds and synthetic studies towards other natural naph- thoquinones starting from juglomycin C are currently underway in our laboratory. 4.1.
